  m_Script: {fileID: 11500000, guid: 3507d679efa283143b52308c9a6a3292, type: 3}
  m_Name: Question_13
  m_EditorClassIdentifier: Assembly-CSharp::QuestionData
  question: Which of the following explains why an AI trained with machine learning
    can rapidly map the best route between two points on a map?
  questionId: 12
  answers:
  - It uses predefined programming instructions to navigate through traffic.
  - It predicts traffic problems based on stored alternative routes for every possible
    situation.
  - It relies on a complete database of all possible routes through the city.
  - It performs millions of tiny calculations quickly, trying different routes through
    trial and error.
  maxSelections: 1
  correctAnswerIndices: 03000000
  correctMessage: An AI trained with machine learning approaches the problem of finding
    the best route like climbing a tree, trying different routes and comparing successful
    ones to identify the shortest route. This process involves performing millions
    of tiny calculations quickly through trial and error.
  incorrectMessage: Not quite. Consider which of the explanations is similar to climbing
    a tree or trying to solve a garden maze.
